# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andrés-pastrana-arango
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1994-colombian-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in Colombia on 29 May 1994, with a second round on 19 June.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1994-colombian-presidential-election] The result was a victory for Ernesto Samper of the Colombian Liberal Party, who received 51% of the vote in the runoff.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1994-colombian-presidential-election] Samper's victory was tainted by the Proceso 8000 scandal, involving accusations that the Liberal Party had sought funding from the Cali Cartel during his campaign and afterward.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1994-colombian-presidential-election] This resulted in an investigation, which found several of Samper's close associates within the party guilty, although Samper himself was absolved of any wrongdoing.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1994-colombian-presidential-election] However, the scandal badly damaged his and his party's reputation during his presidency and resulted in a coalition of opposition politicians forming to oppose him.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1994-colombian-presidential-election] This resulted in the defeat of the Liberal Party in the following 1998 presidential election.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1994-colombian-presidential-election] As of the 2022 presidential election, Samper was Colombia's last Liberal Party president.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1994-colombian-presidential-election] '8000 Process') is the unofficial name given to the corruption scandal surrounding accusations that Colombian Liberal Party candidate Ernesto Samper's 1994 campaign for President of Colombia was partially funded by drug money.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1994-colombian-presidential-election] The name came from the case number issued by the Office of the Attorney General for their investigation into the allegations.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1994-colombian-presidential-election] The investigation formally ended in the mid-1990s.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1994-colombian-presidential-election] The investigation found several of Samper's close associates to be guilty, although Samper himself was absolved of any wrongdoing.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The FARC began their rebel activities in the early 1960s during the National Front years in which bipartisan hegemony controlled and held political power.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] In an effort to exterminate the armed guerrilla movements the Colombian government aided by the United States launched an attack to destroy the "Marquetalia Republic" a guerrilla enclave in central Colombia.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] After this attack the FARC guerrilla retreated to isolated or poor government presence areas and began establishing a parallel state governed by them.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The guerrillas began extorting and kidnapping landowners and assaulting local agrarian banks (*Caja Agrarias*).
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] During the 1980s and 1990s the Colombian drug cartels had increased their power and in some cases had hired the guerrillas such as the FARC and ELN guerrillas to protect illicit cultivations from the government forces.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The most powerful of the cartels; the Medellín and Cali Cartels had engulfed in a war with the government.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The Medellín Cartel led by Pablo Escobar also became an enemy later of the FARC in a struggle to control the profitable illegal drug trafficking business.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Escobar helped create right wing paramilitary groups.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The FARC guerrilla used the revenues from taxing drug lords, and cultivation and production of these to finance their rebel activities.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On August 18, 1989, the Medellín Cartel assassinated the liberal presidential candidate Luis Carlos Galán.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] César Gaviria replaced him and was then elected president of Colombia.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Gaviria avenged the death of Galan by dismantling the Medellín Cartel, but the gap left by this organization was quickly filled by the Cali Cartel and the FARC, which began expanding its influence and armed power in the countryside mainly.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] During the government of Ernesto Samper the opposing candidate Andrés Pastrana accused President Samper of financing its campaign with money from the Cali Cartel.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The political scandal known as the "8000 Process" surged and weakened the presidency and government institutions.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The United States also conditioned its support for the government, focusing mainly on aiding the military forces on operations against narcotics, that would ultimately help bring down the Cali Cartel.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Without any major adversaries in the drug business other than the growing AUC paramilitary group, the FARC gained control of most of the drug production and trade, as well as financing its political rhetoric and influence over most of the regions in Colombia.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] With the weakening of the drug cartels the guerrillas became the main issue affecting Colombia.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Andrés Pastrana ran for the presidential office again and as a candidate his campaign sustained negotiations with the FARC for a possible peace process.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Ricardo as High Commissioner for Peace and held conversations with Manuel Marulanda Velez (aka Tirofijo) top commander of the FARC on June 15, 1998.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On July 9 elected president Pastrana travelled to the mountains of Colombia and personally met with rebel commanders including "Tirofijo" himself.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On October 8 both sides agreed to create a demilitarized zone in the region of El Caguan, a jungle region in south central Colombia made up by the municipalities of Vista Hermosa, La Macarena, La Uribe and Mesetas in Meta Department, and San Vicente del Caguán in Caquetá Department.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On August 7, 1998 Pastrana becomes president of Colombia for the period 1998–2002.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On December 14, 1998, the Pastrana administration and the FARC agreed to begin formal peace talks on January 7, 1999.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The group also considered fundamental topics: democracy, functioning of the state, the public force, social and economic aspects, agrarian reform, natural resources, sovereignty, drug trafficking, paramilitarism and CONVIVIR security groups.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On the other hand, the government tried to persuade the FARC to leave the Colombian Army Cazadores Battalion, stationed in the area of El Caguan, but FARC opposed.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Victor G Ricardo agreed to withdraw the Battalion without consulting military officials.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The government urged the FARC to support projects to manually eradicate illegal crops.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] As planned the formal dialogues began on January 7, 1999, in a ceremony at El Caguan with the presence of President Pastrana, but without the presence of "Tirofijo".
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The FARC argued that there was a possible threat to assassinate their commander "Tirofijo".
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] FARC negotiator Joaquín Gómez acted on behalf of Tirofijo.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] President Pastrana said that "the absence of Manuel Marulanda Velez cannot be a reason to not continue with the instalment of the dialogue to agree on an agenda that will conduct us to peace".
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On January 8, "Tirofijo" showed up and insisted that there had been a possible assassination attempt.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On January 11, guerrilla commander Jorge Briceño threatened to kidnap high-profile people if the government did not comply with FARC's demands for a prisoner exchange.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Some years before, the FARC had kidnapped a considerable number of military personnel, high-profile politicians and government officials.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Pastrana replied with a threat to end the peace process if the FARC carried out the kidnappings.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On January 19 the FARC froze the dialogues that the AUC paramilitary groups were resurging and demanded the government to act against these groups and its supporters within the government.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On February 6 President Pastrana extends the duration of the demilitarized zone and sets it to expire on May 7.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Three days later, Pastrana and "Tirofijo" finally met publicly and set a new meeting on February 14 to resume dialogues.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The FARC had purportedly frozen the peace talks because of the government's spraying of glyphosate to eradicate illegal crops as stated in the Plan Colombia.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Between February 25 and March 11, three American indigenous-rights activists, Terence Freitas, Lahe'ena'e Gay, and Ingrid Washinawatok were abducted by the FARC in Arauca Department and later assassinated.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The FARC admitted the assassination and apologized.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The Colombian government then accused a high ranking FARC member known as Germán Briceño (brother of Jorge Briceño) of the assassination and the United States demanded the FARC to hand over the perpetrators.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] From April 20 to May 1, both parties met unofficially in El Caguan to discuss the paramilitary issue and the FARC's demands to expand the area of the demilitarized zone, which was due to expire on May 7, and to extend the timeframe.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On May 2, President Pastrana travelled to the demilitarized zone and personally met with "Tirofijo" for a second time.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Pastrana convinced him to begin formal peace-talks on May 6.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] It was agreed that the demilitarized area would remain in size, but its expiration would be postponed.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Another decision was to form an International Verification Commission to observe the agreements and the FARC's actions in the area.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On May 26, Colombian Minister of Defense, Rodrigo Lloreda resigned after criticising the president's handling of the peace process.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Lloreda opposed the indefinite extension of the timeline of the demilitarized area.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The High Commissioner for Peace's remarks suggesting an extension of the demilitarized area for the FARC triggered a discontent in some servicemen in the Colombian military; 18 generals also tried to resign but the president only accepted Lloreda's.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Fernando Tapias, offered President Pastrana a public show of support.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Pastrana then appointed Luis Fernando Ramírez as Defense Minister.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The Center for International Policy led a delegation of US Congressmen to Colombia.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] Among the representatives was William Delahunt (D-MA) and six other members of Congress, who met with government officials and representatives of political parties, church groups, peace groups, human rights groups, US government employees stationed in Colombia and the United Nations.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On June 4 the delegation of US representatives travelled to El Caguan to meet with rebel leaders.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] They held talks without results with guerrilla commander Raúl Reyes regarding the drug trade, kidnappings and the assassination of US citizens, specially related to the three US indigenous workers.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The government then announced that the formal negotiations with the FARC would begin on July 7.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The Military of Colombia, with the help of the U.S. government, counterattacked by bombing guerrilla enclaves using U.S. provided satellite intelligence.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] On July 15, 1999 Defense Minister Luis Fernando Ramírez and the Colombian General of the Chief of Staff Fernando Tapias requested US$500 million as aid to fund counter-narcotics and counter-insurgency warfare.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/1999-2002-farc-government-peace-process] The then head of the US Office of National Drug Control Policy Barry McCaffrey called for a billion dollar as supplemental assistance for the war on drugs in South America, half of it to be assigned to Colombia.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] General elections were held in Argentina on 22 October 2023 to elect the president, vice president, members of the National Congress, and the governors of most provinces.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] As no presidential candidate won a majority in the first round, a run-off was held on 19 November, in which Buenos Aires Deputy Javier Milei defeated Economy Minister Sergio Massa by 11% of the votes, to become President of Argentina.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Incumbent president Alberto Fernández and incumbent vice president and former president Cristina Fernández de Kirchner, despite both being eligible for a second, consecutive term, did not seek re-election.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Advancing to the run-off, Massa of the ruling centre-left Union for the Homeland unexpectedly came in first place, winning 36% of the vote, against Milei of the right-wing Liberty Advances, who came in second place, with 30% of the vote.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Massa's victory in the first round was seen as an upset because of the severe inflation that took place during Massa's tenure as economy minister, as well as Milei's lead in polls up to that point.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] In the run-off, Milei defeated Massa with 56% of the vote, the highest percentage of the vote since Argentina's transition to democracy.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Milei received over 14 million votes, which was the highest-ever vote total in Argentina's history.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] In a surprise reversal of the first round, Milei outperformed polls, which had been predicting a much closer race.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Massa conceded defeat shortly before the official results were published.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Observers generally saw Milei's win as a sign more of discontent with the *status quo* than support for his politics, and his victory was likened to that of Donald Trump's 2016 victory in the United States and Jair Bolsonaro's 2018 victory in Brazil.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Milei expressed support and admiration for both figures, and endorsed Trump in the 2024 United States presidential election.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Macri became the first incumbent president in Argentine history to be defeated for reelection.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] The first two years of the Fernández presidency were limited by the COVID-19 pandemic in Argentina, during which he imposed strict lockdown measures in an attempt to suppress the spread of the disease, and a debt crisis.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] While the economy did recover in 2021–22, inflation rose to 100% (the highest since 1991).
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] His approval ratings were low throughout his presidency, rarely cresting 50%, while disapproval ranged from 60% to 80%.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] In 2020, *The Economist* declared him "a president without a plan", and his presidency a "weak administration", alluding to his lack of independent decision-making and the admitted influence on him of Vice President and former President Cristina Fernández de Kirchner.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] The 2021 midterm elections resulted in heavy losses for the Frente de Todos, which lost its majority in both houses of Congress.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Observers attributed the loss to widespread anger over high inflation and rising poverty.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] In April 2023, Fernández announced that he had decided not to seek reelection to the presidency in the 2023 general election.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Others who refused to run were incumbent vice president Cristina Fernández de Kirchner (who served as president between 2007 and 2015), and former president Mauricio Macri, who succeeded Fernández de Kirchner and preceded Fernández.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Controversial constitutional amendments in Jujuy – a province governed by Gerardo Morales, who ran as a precandidate for vice president alongside Horacio Rodriguez Larreta– led to protests beginning in June where demonstrators stormed the Jujuy legislature.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] The 2023 election was held amid a severe economic crisis with over 140% inflation and 40% poverty which observers said would negatively affect the ruling party's chance for another term.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] The election of the president is conducted under the ballotage system, a modified version of the two-round system.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] A candidate can win the presidency in a single round by either winning over 45% of the vote or if they win 40% of the vote while finishing more than 10 percentage points ahead of the second-place candidate.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] If no candidate meets either threshold, a runoff takes place between the top two candidates.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Voting is compulsory for citizens between 18 and 70 years old.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Suffrage is also extended to 16- and 17-year-olds, though without compulsory voting.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Both in the primaries and in the first and second rounds polls opened at 08:00 and closed at 18:00 (UTC −3), with vote results starting to show at around 21:00.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] The 257 members of the Chamber of Deputies are elected by proportional representation in 24 multi-member constituencies based on the provinces (plus the City of Buenos Aires).
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Seats are allocated using the d'Hondt method with a 3% electoral threshold.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] In this election, 130 of the 257 seats were up for renewal for a four-year term.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] The 72 members of the Senate are elected in the same 24 constituencies, with three seats in each.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] The party receiving the most votes in each constituency wins two seats, with the third seat awarded to the second-placed party.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] The 2023 elections will see one-third of senators renewed, with eight provinces electing three senators for a 6-year term; Buenos Aires, Formosa, Jujuy, La Rioja, Misiones, San Juan, San Luis, and Santa Cruz.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] The following candidates participated in the Open, Simultaneous and Mandatory Primaries (PASO), which were held on 13 August 2023.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] The primaries determined the candidates of each coalition.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p01] Coalitions who received less than 1.5% of the votes will not be able to participate in the general election on 22 October.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Milei defeated Massa in the runoff what was described as a historic election in Argentina.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Milei in his victory speech vowed to begin "the reconstruction of Argentina" and end the country's economic decline.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] His prospective foreign minister Diana Mondino also announced Argentina would pause their accession to BRICS.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Massa conceded and announced his retirement from politics after the runoff election results showed that he had lost by roughly 11 percentage points.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Incumbent and retiring president Alberto Fernández congratulated Milei: "I am a man of democracy, and I value nothing more than the popular verdict.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] I trust that tomorrow we can start working with Javier Milei to guarantee an orderly transition." Former president Mauricio Macri, who had endorsed Milei in the runoff, said: "I congratulate Javier Milei for bravely representing the will to advance and prosper that lives in the hearts of Argentines.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Bolivia: Bolivian president Luis Arce wished success to Javier Milei and said that he would work hard to keep "firm relations" with Argentina.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Brazil: Brazilian president Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva congratulated Milei without mentioning his name, saying: "Democracy is the voice of the people, and it must always be respected.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] My congratulations to Argentine institutions for conducting the electoral process and to the Argentine people who participated on election day in an orderly and peaceful manner.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] I wish the new government good luck and success." Former president Jair Bolsonaro congratulated Milei saying: "Congratulations to the Argentine people for Javier Milei's victory.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Chile: Chilean president Gabriel Boric congratulated Milei saying: "I salute Javier Milei for his victory and Sergio Massa for his worthy recognition of defeat.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] I wish the Argentine people the best and know that they will always have our respect and support.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Colombia: Colombian president Gustavo Petro lamented Milei's win, which was mocked by El Salvador president Nayib Bukele.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] European Union: Charles Michel, the president of the European Council, congratulated Milei saying: "Congratulations to Argentina's new president-elect Javier Milei for his victory.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Ilan Goldfajn, the president of the Inter-American Development Bank, congratulated Milei saying: "Congratulations Javier Milei, president-elect of Argentina.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] India: Indian prime minister Narendra Modi congratulated Milei saying: "Congratulations for the victory in the Presidential elections.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Mexico: Mexican president Andrés Manuel López Obrador called Argentina's election of Milei an "own goal".
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Peru: Peruvian president Dina Boluarte congratulated Milei saying: "Peru expresses its warm congratulations to Javier Milei for his election as president of the Argentine Republic.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Russia: Russian president Vladimir Putin congratulated Milei, despite the latter support for Ukraine in the Russo-Ukrainian War.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Putin's press secretary Dmitry Peskov said: "We noted a number of statements that Mr.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Ukraine: Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy congratulated Milei on his victory and thanked him for his clear stance of support for Ukraine.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Zelenskyy further stated that he looked forward to working together with Milei to strengthen Ukrainian-Argentinian cooperation and restore international order based on international law.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Zelenskyy and Milei held a phone call where they discussed cultivating relations and Ukraine's war against Russia.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] United States: U.S president Joe Biden congratulated Milei and held a phone call with him, where Biden said that Argentina can count on US support.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Milei told Biden that he would align with the US and Israel, while repeatedly saying that he would cool relations with China.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Antony Blinken, the United States Secretary of State, congratulated Milei saying: "The United States congratulates Argentine President-elect Javier Milei on his victory in today's election, and we applaud the robust democratic process through which the Argentine public has spoken.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] The strong turnout and peaceful conduct of the vote are a testament to Argentina's electoral and democratic institutions.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] We look forward to building on our strong bilateral relationship based on our shared commitment to human rights, democratic values, and transparency." Former president Donald Trump congratulated Milei saying: "Congratulations to Javier Milei on a great race for president of Argentina.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Uruguay: Uruguayan president Luis Lacalle Pou congratulated Milei saying: "I salute President-elect Javier Milei.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/2023-argentine-general-election-p02] Venezuela: Venezuelan president Nicolás Maduro, reacting to the election results, declared that "the neo-Nazi extreme right won in Argentina, we call for reflection on the emergence of extreme right centers that seek to impose themselves to recolonize Latin America and impose extremist models".
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Born in Bayan Lepas, Penang, Abdullah was educated at the University of Malaya and began his career in the Malaysian civil service before entering politics in 1978 as the Member of Parliament for Kepala Batas, a seat he held until 2013.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] He later served in several ministerial portfolios, including education, defence and foreign affairs, before being appointed deputy prime minister under Mahathir Mohamad.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah assumed the premiership following Mahathir's resignation in 2003 and initially enjoyed strong public support, promoting institutional reform, anti-corruption measures, and a vision of moderate Islam through his concept of Islam Hadhari.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] His administration focused on economic development and regional growth initiatives, but his later years in office were marked by economic challenges, declining public approval, and criticism over governance and media freedom.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] These factors contributed to significant losses for the ruling coalition in the 2008 Malaysian general election, after which he stepped down in 2009.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah was born on 26 November 1939 in Kampung Perlis, Bayan Lepas, Penang, into a prominent religious family.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] His paternal grandfather, Syeikh Abdullah Badawi Fahim, was of Hadrami descent and was a respected religious scholar and nationalist.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] He was among the founding members of Hizbul Muslimin, which later evolved into the Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party (PAS), and served as the first Mufti of Penang following Malaysia’s independence.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] His father, Ahmad Badawi, was a religious teacher and active member of UMNO.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] His mother, Kailan Haji Hassan, died in Kuala Lumpur on 2 February 2004 at the age of 80.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah's maternal grandfather, Ha Su-chiang (simplified Chinese: 哈苏璋; traditional Chinese: 哈蘇璋; pinyin: *Hā Sūzhāng*), also known as Hassan Salleh, was an Utsul Muslim from Sanya, Hainan.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah received his early education at Permatang Bertam Primary School, Kepala Batas from 1947.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Then, he continued his secondary education at Bukit Mertajam High School and later attended Methodist Boys' School, Penang for his sixth form.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] In 1964, he graduated from the University of Malaya with a Bachelor of Arts degree in Islamic Studies.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] After graduating from the University of Malaya, he joined the Malaysian Administrative and Diplomatic Corps (PTD) in 1964.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] He served as Director of Youth's Ministry Department at the Ministry of Youth and Sport as well as member of the National Operations Council (MAGERAN).
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] He resigned in 1978 to become a member of parliament for his constituency of Kepala Batas in northern Seberang Perai (which had also been represented by his father).
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] After Abdullah was elected as the Member of Parliament (MP) for Kepala Batas in 1978 general election, he served as the parliamentary secretary to the minister of federal territories from 1978 until 1980 and deputy minister of federal territories from 1980 until 1981.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Brought on as a minister without portfolio in 1981, he was responsible for the implementation of the Look East policy.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] However, he did not join the now-defunct Semangat 46 (Spirit 46) splinter party set up by Tengku Razaleigh.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Instead, Mahathir brought Abdullah into the pro tem committee of the reconstituted UMNO (Baru) or New UMNO as its vice-president upon the party's founding in February 1988.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] During a cabinet reshuffle in 1991, Mahathir brought him back into government as the minister of foreign affairs.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Despite losing the vice presidency in the 1993 UMNO elections, he remained in government.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] In January 1999, Abdullah was appointed acting deputy president in UMNO and deputy prime minister, replacing Anwar Ibrahim in both roles after the latter was removed removed from government, expelled from UMNO, and arrested, sparking the Reformasi movement.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Chosen by Mahathir as his candidate for deputy president in the 2000 United Malays National Organisation leadership election, Abdullah was perceived as a political lightweight that did not possess enough political influence or support to challenge Mahathir's preeminence within the party.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] This was attributed to his refusal to engage in money politics, which prevented him from building a base.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] The election was held under rules that prohibited anyone else from contesting the positions of president and deputy president.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Becoming prime minister after Mahathir's resignation in October 2003, Abdullah entered office espousing a populist reform agenda.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Multiple anti-corruption investigations were also launched against government officials and businessmen that resulted in arrests.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] He also broke with past practice and appointed professionals to head government-linked companies instead of politicians, calling for an end to the culture of the "iron rice bowl" and towards a culture rewarding performance.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] However, observers noted that redelineation exercises the previous year under Mahathir also played a factor in the scale of victory.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] The momentum of reform slowed after the 2004 general election, and Malaysia's ranking in that year's Corruption Perceptions Index fell two places from 37th to 39th.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Instead, Abdullah shifted towards attempting a reform of political culture within the country, introducing the concept of *Islam Hadhari*, a moderate-to-progressive interpretation of Islam that called for religious tolerance and modernity.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Crucially, it appropriated what had been the opposition Malaysian Islamic Party (PAS)'s themes of social justice and distributive equality that had helped them secure electoral gains against UMNO in the 1999 Malaysian general election.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] On the economic front, Malaysia experienced steady economic growth throughout Abdullah's years in office, but inflation remained a persistent issue.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Under his administration, the Malaysian ringgit's peg to the US Dollar was ended in 2005.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] The agricultural sector, traditionally neglected in favour of the industrial and services industries, received significant investment from Abdullah's government.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] When rising costs led to the government lowering petrol subsidies in 2006, street protests were launched in response.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] These were violently dispersed by riot police.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Further plans for restructuring government subsidies in the face of rising fuel prices internationally also faced criticism as Malaysia was at the time a net exporter of petroleum and natural gas.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] The Ninth Malaysia Plan launched by Abdullah covering government expenditure from 2006 to 2010 retained much of the costly and divisive positive discriminatory measures introduced by the New Economic Policy.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] By 2007, a slew of scandals had left a severe dent in public confidence in Abdullah's premiership.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah himself was also accused of engaging in nepotism.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Mahathir had also began to openly criticise Abdullah after the latter cancelled a major infrastructure project in 2006, one of the last decided upon by Mahathir before he left office, going as far as saying he regretted choosing Abdullah as his successor.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Conversely, his administration's decision to resume a number of high-profile mega-projects such as the Bakun Dam elicited public criticism in the face of rising costs of living.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] The continued deterioration of relations between the country's ethnic and religious groups coincided with a rise in Islamist sentiment in the country that the government promoted, with Abdullah openly referring to the country as an "Islamic state".
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] The government at this time was also rocked by two successive large-scale public protests, the first for free-and-fair elections and the second by the country's Indian minority against racial discrimination.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Both were dispersed with the use of tear gas and chemical-laced water cannons by armed riot police.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] As many as 12 members of the opposition were also arrested for their participation in the protests which were deemed illegal.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] These events precipitated Barisan Nasional's poor showing in the 2008 Malaysian general election held in March, where the ruling coalition lost its two-thirds majority in parliament and control over four state governments to a united opposition riding on popular discontent.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] In contrast to Mahathir, Abdullah's administration adopted a "moderate and low profile approach" to foreign policy, doing away with the former's confrontational, often anti-Western attitude.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Relations with Singapore, with whom the previous administration frequently clashed with over issues such as Batu Puteh and the supply of raw water improved.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Meanwhile, relations with Myanmar and Thailand cooled as a result of the former's persecution of Rohingya Muslims and the latter's killings of ethnic Malays during the South Thailand insurgency.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah's promotion of Islam Hadhari in the context of the war on terror was welcomed by the United States, with whom the Malaysian government cooperated with in the former's efforts to combat Islamist terrorism internationally.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Nevertheless, it opposed the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Negotiations for a free trade agreement with the United States began in 2005 but were never concluded.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Relations were complicated when it was revealed that a Malaysian company was manufacturing parts for the Libyan nuclear programme and various Malaysian companies were implicated in smuggling military parts to Iran.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] During Abdullah's tenure, Malaysia sought closer ties with China and signed several agreements as part of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), including the ASEAN–China free trade agreement.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Malaysia and China also released two joint communiqués and signed a memorandum of understanding on defence cooperation in 2004 and 2005.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah's government supported both the United States and China's efforts to resolve the issue of North Korean nuclear proliferation through the Six-Party Talks, and Kuala Lumpur served as a platform for secret meetings and negotiations.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Despite the ongoing Darfur genocide, Abdullah's government continued to invest in Sudan's oil industry, in which Malaysia was the second-largest shareholder behind China.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah expressed support for the Sudanese government's policy towards Darfur.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Blamed for the coalition's poor performance in the 2008 Malaysian general election, Abdullah was put under increasing pressure to resign as prime minister by coalition partners and UMNO leaders alike.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Mahathir's announcement that he was leaving UMNO in May was widely understood as an attempt to force Abdullah's resignation.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] There were also fears that Sabah and Sarawak-based parties in the Barisan Nasional coalition might switch allegiances to the opposition led by Anwar Ibrahim.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] On 10 July 2008, Abdullah announced he would step down as UMNO president and prime minister in 2009.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] During the UMNO general assembly on 1 April 2009, Abdullah stood down as party president in favour of his deputy, Najib Razak and was succeeded by him as prime minister on 3 April 2009.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah was subsequently conferred with the title of "Tun" by the King of Malaysia, Mizan Zainal Abidin for his services to the nation.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah met Endon while he was working at the Federal Establishment Office (now the Public Service Department) in the 1960s and they were married in 1965.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] They had two children, a son Kamaluddin Abdullah and a daughter, Nori Abdullah, who is married to Khairy Jamaluddin.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Both Abdullah and Endon had four grandchildren.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] On 20 October 2005, Abdullah Badawi's wife, Endon Mahmood, died of breast cancer.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Endon discovered the disease in 2003 while her twin sister Noraini, who had earlier been diagnosed with the same illness, died in January 2003.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] She received treatment in the United States and returned to Malaysia 18 days before her death.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] She is buried at a Muslim cemetery, at Taman Selatan, Precinct 20, Putrajaya.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] On 6 June 2007, the Prime Minister's office announced Abdullah Badawi's marriage to Jeanne Abdullah.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] On 9 June, a private ceremony was conducted at the Prime Minister's residence, Seri Perdana, and attended by close relatives.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Jeanne was formerly married to Endon Mahmood’s younger brother.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] She was also a manager at the Seri Perdana residential complex and has two children from her previous marriage.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah was criticised for allowing his son-in-law, Khairy Jamaluddin, to become unduly influential in UMNO politics.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah was also criticised for allowing his brother Fahim Ibrahim Badawi to buy 51 percent of the government-controlled MAS Catering Sdn Bhd.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Fahim later sold this stake to Lufthansa's LSG Skychef at a huge profit.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] His poem, "*I Seek Eternal Peace*" was translated into more than 80 languages and published as a book.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] On 11 September 2022, Abdullah's son-in-law and former health minister, Khairy Jamaluddin, publicly revealed that Abdullah had been battling dementia and was no longer able to recognise family members or communicate effectively.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] In the years that followed, his declining health kept him away from the public eye and he required the assistance of a wheelchair.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] In 2024, he was admitted to the hospital due to spontaneous pneumothorax.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Abdullah died following complications from multi-organ failure at the National Heart Institute in Kuala Lumpur, on 14 April 2025, at the age of 85.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] The next day, his body lay in state at the main prayer hall of the National Mosque from 10 am to 1 pm, before being laid to rest at the Heroes' Mausoleum at around 2:30 pm.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] All four living former prime ministers—Mahathir Mohamad, Najib Razak, Muhyiddin Yassin and Ismail Sabri Yaakob—also paid their final respects.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/abdullah-ahmad-badawi] Actress Michelle Yeoh and Singaporean musician Ramli Sarip also paid their respects.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] Lleras Camargo served as congressman of Colombia.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] He was also a cousin of later president Carlos Lleras Restrepo.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] He died in 1990 after suffering a long illness.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] He attended the traditional Colegio Mayor de Nuestra Señora del Rosario.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] In 1929, he was elected deputy assemblyman on the Bogotá city council, his first entrance into politics.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] The following year he became Secretary of the Executive Committee of the Colombian Liberal Party and in 1931, he was elected to the Colombian Chamber of Representatives.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] That same year, he became the first Liberal to preside over the Chamber in more than forty years.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] After Alfonso López Pumarejo was elected President of Colombia in 1934, Lleras Camargo was named Cabinet Secretary.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] In 1935, he became the Minister of Government, a position he occupied until the end of López Pumarejo's presidential term in 1938.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] In 1938, he founded the newspaper *El Liberal*, which promoted López Pumarejo's re-election.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] In 1941, he returned to and once again presided over the Chamber of Representatives.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] When López Pumarejo was re-elected president in 1942, he once again named Lleras Camargo the Minister of Government.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] Aside from a brief interruption in 1943, when Lleras Camargo became the Colombian Ambassador to the United States, he occupied that position until 1944, when intense political instability disrupted López Pumarejo's presidency.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] In July 1944, after López Pumarejo stepped down, Lleras Camargo fought off a coup attempt against Darío Echandía, who had been temporarily designated as president.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] In 1945, he became Minister of Foreign Relations, and in that capacity, represented Colombia at the Chapultepec Conference and the United Nations Conference on International Organization in San Francisco, which created the United Nations.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] But that same year, the Senate named designated him as Acting President, a position he occupied until 1946, when Conservative Mariano Ospina Pérez was elected president.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] At only thirty-nine years-old, he became one of the youngest acting presidents in Colombian history.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] During his short year in office, the Greater Colombian Merchant Fleet was founded and the Constitutional Reform of 1945 completed.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] On May 29, 1926, Lleras, then 19 years old, participated in a march in support of Laureano Gómez, the Minister of Public Works under President Pedro Nel Ospina, whose plans to build a road had been blocked by the Council of State.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] It is known that Germán Arciniegas, seeing Lleras's fears about delivering his speech in defense of Gómez, decided to carry him to give the young man confidence.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] After leaving the presidency in 1946, Lleras Camargo founded the highly regarded news magazine *Semana*.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] Owing to the respect and prestige he had earned as Minister of Foreign Relations and President of Colombia, he was named Director of the Pan American Union in 1947.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] He launched a restructuring effort, which culminated in the founding the Organization of American States in 1948.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] Lleras Camargo served as the first General Secretary between 1948-1949 and later completed a full five-year term between 1950 and 1954.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alberto-lleras-camargo] During his second term, the organization became more consolidated as a hemispheric organization, with increased continental participation.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] López was the son of former two-time president of Colombia, Alfonso López Pumarejo and his first wife María Michelsen Lombana, who was of Danish descent.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] He studied at the *Gimnasio Moderno* School and later in other cities: Paris, Brussels, London and Santiago de Chile.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] He graduated with a degree in law from the Universidad del Rosario.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] During his father's presidency, López maintained a low profile in politics and instead focused on becoming a university professor at the *Universidad del Rosario*.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] In 1938, López married Cecilia Caballero Blanco in Bogotá and they had three sons.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] They moved to the outskirts of Bogotá in a *hacienda* in the then municipality of Engativá, Cundinamarca Department (nowadays a Locality of Bogotá).
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] Settled in this town, López had his first experience of politics becoming a town councilman.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] During this time, his fellow councilmen included two other politicians who went on to become key political players in the country, Álvaro Gómez Hurtado and future president Julio César Turbay Ayala.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] In 1959, a group of his former college students founded the Liberal Revolutionary Movement (MRL) as a reaction against the pact between the Liberal Party and the Conservative Party to create the National Front, in which the two parties took turns to govern.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] López Michelsen was then offered the leadership of the newly created MRL and he accepted, becoming a presidential candidate for the 1962 presidential elections.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] López lost the election by a large margin to Conservative candidate Guillermo León Valencia.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] In 1966, López was elected as a senator and negotiated the return of the MRL to the Liberal Party in 1967.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] This same year López traveled to the city of Valledupar after being appointed by President Carlos Lleras Restrepo as the first governor of Cesar Department, a newly created province in the northern Caribbean Region of Colombia.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] López was able to trace his grandmothers' family ancestors "the Pumarejos," back to this town.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] During those years, he was also instrumental in the creation of the Vallenato Legend Festival (nowadays, one of the most important cultural events in Colombia) along with vallenato composer Rafael Escalona and journalist Consuelo Araújo.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] He served as governor of Cesar from 21 December 1967, until 14 August 1968.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] A year later, he was appointed Minister of Foreign Affairs until the end of the presidential term of President Carlos Lleras Restrepo in 1970.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] In 1974, López was chosen by the Liberal Party as their candidate for president, after defeating former president Carlos Lleras Restrepo in the party presidential primaries, with the support of former candidate (and presidential successor) Julio César Turbay.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] He won the general election by a large margin against the Conservative Party candidate Álvaro Gómez Hurtado, and the ANAPO candidate, María Eugenia Rojas.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] His 2,929,719 votes were the highest ever for any president until that time.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] His inaugural presidential speech, delivered on 7 August 1974, is mostly remembered for calling the disputed border area in the Gulf of Venezuela by its native indigenous name, "Gulf of Coquibacoa" given by the Wayuus.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] In his speech he also promised to reduce the growing gap between farmer and urban populations and to fight poverty, messages that attracted the support of many left-wing political movements.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] He also introduced a tax and fiscal reform which increased national saving, and allowed an increase in public investment and exports.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] Crop production increased 16%, and he also created public offices devoted to the improvement of farming.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] Under his government, also, power grids were expanded, and infrastructure investment increased.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] In contrast, inflation reached under his government its highest historical values, at around 32%.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] Early support for his policies soon turned to fierce opposition, as many of his campaign promises, in particular those to make deals with unions and in the improvement of potable water access, went unfulfilled, and as subsidies were eliminated and inflation rose.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] Unions and other leftist activists had been accumulating frustration and resentment for decades after the killing of Jorge Eliécer Gaitán, and the subsequent violence, and the hope for a more open society that came with Lopez's election turned into feelings of betrayal.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] As a result, and after three years as president the major Colombian Unions got together and managed to propose and organize a massive, general strike.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] The López administration took a hard approach towards the planned strike, calling it subversive and at some point threatening arrest and forbidding public meetings.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] This only enraged the participants, and the major unionists were joined by teachers, students, independent workers, housewives, guerrilla leaders, and even members of the opposition conservative party.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] The organizing committee demanded among other things salary increases, frozen prices for essential goods and public services fees, re-establishment of the right to meet and strike, and a reduction in work hours.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] The strike, occurring on 14 September 1977, came to be known as the National Civil Strike, and it attracted such a large number of discontented participants that the organizing committee soon lost control of it.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] Major roads were blocked all over Bogota, and in many other cities around the country, and very soon many small skirmishes between protesters and riot police started occurring all over.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] The manifestations and skirmishes soon turned into riots, and protesters started pillaging big stores and vandalizing factories and cars.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] By 4 pm the major declared curfew which only made protesters more enraged.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] Hundreds of protesters were wounded, and thousands were arrested and assembled in the city's Soccer stadium and bullfighting arena.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] Riots and skirmishes continued all night and well into the next day, which devastated the city.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] About 20 or 30 people died in the middle of it.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] As a consequence, unions declared victory and the López Michelsen's government had to make concessions.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] However, the riot made his government adopt a harsher, more repressive stance.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] Upon the end of his term in 1978, he again became the leader of Liberal Party.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] He ran for president again in 1982, but was defeated by the Conservative Party candidate, Belisario Betancur.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] He continued to actively participate in the decision making of the Liberal Party until the early 1990s when he decided to withdraw from political activity.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] He was a regular columnist for the Colombian newspaper *El Tiempo* which drew attention to many critical issues.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] For this reason he was called "*el hombre que pone a pensar al pais*" (Spanish for "The man who makes the country think").
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-michelsen] Lopez Michelsen died in Bogotá on 11 July 2007, after suffering a heart attack.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] Born in Honda, Tolima, López is a prominent leader of the Liberal Party in Tolima.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] During his first presidency, he spearheaded the "Revolution in March," which promoted state modernization, social justice, and constitutional reform.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] He also championed secular education, free from state and church interference.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] Alfonso López Pumarejo was born in Honda (Tolima) to Pedro Aquilino López Medina, a businessman and Rosario Pumarejo Cotes.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] Alfonso López Pumarejo went on to study at the London School of Economics.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] His son, Alfonso López Michelsen, was president of Colombia between 1974 and 1978.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] The first administration of Alfonso López Pumarejo (1934–38) known as the "revolución en marcha", has proven an enduring theme of historical interest.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] López ran a campaign emphasizing reform, welfare programs, liberal democracy, constitutional reform, education reform (moving away from Church-provided education to public education), expansion of male suffrage, and land reform to redistribute idle land to the landless.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] Several radical changes were promoted during his first administration, as the government supported the creation of labour unions and also passed the Law 200 of 1936, which allowed for the expropriation of private properties, in order to promote "social interest".
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] His government dismantled exchange controls in 1935.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] His government liberalized regulations on foreign investment in Colombia, stimulating increased investment in banana and oil production.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] He signed a commercial treaty with the United States in 1935.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] These actions earned López Pumarejo the backing of important rural and labour sectors, in addition to that of the Colombian Communist Party, but they likewise divided his previous political allies, some of which called for moderation.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] The election of his successor Eduardo Santos Montejo took place in 1938.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] After being re-elected in 1942, the second administration of López Pumarejo faced a stronger opposition in Congress and by both the more conservative and more radical sectors within the president's own Colombian Liberal Party which resulted in the interruption of previous reforms.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] To permit López Pumarejo to travel to the United States and care for his sick wife, María Michelsen de López, Darío Echandía assumed the acting presidency of the country from 17 November 1943 to 16 May 1944.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] This turn of events also prevented the development of further reforms, as López himself was temporarily removed from the political arena.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] After his return to the country, further political conflicts led to a failed military coup attempt in 1944 wherein López Pumarejo was briefly kidnapped, and López Pumarejo finally resigned in early 1945.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] In 1946, he was head of the Colombian delegation to the United Nations.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] Alfonso López Pumarejo died on 20 November 1959 in London, to which he had travelled as Colombia's ambassador to the United Kingdom.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] He had lived at 33 Wilton Crescent in Belgravia, Knightsbridge in London with his second wife, Olga Dávila Alzamora.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] They married in 1953 after both their spouses had died (she had been married to Leopoldo Kopp Castello, son of well-known industrialist Leo Kopp (es), founder of Bavaria Brewery).
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/alfonso-lópez-pumarejo] López's body was taken by horse-drawn carriage from his residency to Westminster Cathedral where a funeral mass was held in his name.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Pastrana was born on 17 August 1954 in Bogotá to Misael Pastrana Borrero, who later served as the 23rd President of Colombia, and María Cristina Arango Vega, the former First Lady of Colombia.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] During his father's presidency, he was a high school student at Colegio San Carlos where he served as president of the student council and graduated in 1973.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] He later acquired a degree in law at the Our Lady of the Rosary University in 1977, and attended Harvard University as a 1978 Weatherhead Center for International Affairs Fellow.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] He founded the magazine *Guión* and a *programadora* known as Datos y Mensajes, whose flagship program was the newscast *Noticiero TV Hoy*.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] As a regular news anchor he became a nationally known figure.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] In 1982, he formally began his political career by gaining a seat on the local Bogotá council.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] He also specialized in press articles on the production and trafficking of cocaine for which he gained many journalistic awards.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] He was kidnapped on January 18, 1988, in Antioquia by the Medellín Cartel, which was pressuring the Colombian government into preventing the extradition of Pablo Escobar and other drug lords to the United States.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] He was found by the National Police a week later, and in March, he was elected Mayor of Bogotá, a position that he held until 1990.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] In 1994, he stood for the presidency against the Liberal candidate, Ernesto Samper, and lost by only 2% in the second round.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Pastrana immediately accused Samper of using drug money to finance his campaign and provided audio recordings to the authorities that subsequently attracted much media attention and eventually led to a scandal known as *8.000 Process* (*Proceso 8.000*).
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] While the accusation underwent a parliamentary investigation, Pastrana retired into his private life.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] In 1998, Pastrana announced his intention to run for president.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] This time, he won that year's presidential election.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Former paramilitary Salvatore Mancuso, commander of the AUC, admitted in 2023 that his organisation had supported Andres Pastrana's presidential campaign in 2002.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] His presidency is remembered for his negotiations with the two left-wing guerrilla groups FARC and ELN, culminating in the grant of a demilitarized safe haven to the guerrillas the size of Switzerland, and for his breaking off the negotiations.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] It is also remembered for a growing degree of unpopularity in polls as his term progressed.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Some critics accused him of possibly accepting unspecified bribes from leading FARC and ELN members, but no concrete evidence of that was presented during his presidency.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] He was also heavily criticized for all the seemingly-pleasure trips that he took around the world during his term.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] President Bill Clinton launched Plan Colombia to fight the communist guerrillas with the payment by the United States of $1.6 billion over three years to the Colombian army.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] In 2002, he supported the ousting of Hugo Chávez and the Interim Government of Pedro Carmona.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Military counterguerrilla operations caused the forced displacement of more than one million people in four years.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Cocaine production increased by 47% during that period.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] After consulting his family and his political supporters, Pastrana accepted.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Some political analysts theorized that Uribe considered that Pastrana would be a useful diplomat in Washington because he would help to renegotiate Plan Colombia and in general to maintain U.S. aid to Colombia, which has contributed to the successes of the Uribe administration.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] In July 2006, a few days after Uribe had appointed former President Ernesto Samper as Colombian ambassador to France, Pastrana told Uribe that he was "morally impeded" from participating in a government along with ex-President Samper.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Pastrana resigned and returned to Colombia, and Samper rejected his own appointment.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] However, that move was not well received by the Conservative Party, which was committed to Uribe, who had won the presidency as an independent, and left Pastrana alone.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Pastrana had a close friendship with Ghislaine Maxwell since 2002.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] According to Maxwell, they met in a pub in Dublin, and Pastrana invited Maxwell and Epstein to Colombia to fly Colombian army helicopters.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] In 2003, Pastrana visited Maxwell and Epstein in New York and Palm Beach, invited them to meet Fidel Castro in Cuba, and maintained email correspondence with Maxwell.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] According to the Epstein files, in 2009, Epstein emailed Jean-Luc Brunel with instructions involving Pastrana.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Brunel emailed Pastrana, indicating prior acquaintance and enthusiasm to reconnect.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Pastrana is a board member in the International Foundation for Electoral Systems, and the honorary president of the *Union of Latin American Parties* (UPLA).
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] He is also a member of the Fondation Chirac's honour committee, and of the Club de Madrid, a group of more than 80 former leaders of democratic countries, which works to strengthen democratic leadership worldwide.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Pastrana also serves on the board of advisors for the Global Panel Foundation, and as a counsellor for the One Young World Dublin summit in 2014, along with four other former presidents from Latin American countries.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] He now maintains a distant and hostile relationship with his own party, even referring to it as "absolutely corrupt".
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] He has also levied accusations of corruption against two of the most prominent party leaders, Efraín Cepeda and Hernán Andrade.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] He campaigned in 2016 against the peace agreements signed between the Colombian government and the guerrilla.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] He supported far-right candidate Javier Milei in 2023 Argentine general election.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] In 2013, Pastrana was awarded the Hanno R.
[src:andrés-pastrana-arango/andrés-pastrana-arango] Ellenbogen Citizenship Award jointly by the Prague Society for International Cooperation and Global Panel Foundation.
